    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-04-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-04-04T18:00:00-05:00" n="241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.61/720: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-04-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 4, 1940—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>197. You are commended for the able manner in which you replied to Lozovski’s
                    complaints as set forth in your 332 of March 28.</p>
                <p>The Soviet Ambassador made similar complaints to me yesterday<note n="98"
                        xml:id="d241fn98">See memorandum of April 2 by the Secretary of State, <ref
                            target="#pg_266">p. 266</ref>.</note> during the course of a long
                    conversation in which we discussed the whole field of American-Soviet relations.
                    He asked in particular whether this Government intended to break off commercial
                    relations with the Soviet Union, and again raised the question of the moral
                    embargo. I made it clear to him that this Government was not <pb facs="0289"
                        n="277" xml:id="pg_277"/> responsible for such disturbances as may exist in
                    Soviet-American relations. I gave the Ambassador no definite reply as to when
                    the moral embargo would terminate, pointing out to him that we do not know
                    whether the Soviet Union will embark upon another war and will engage again in
                    the bombing of civilians.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
